YOO YES KIAAN if youre talking about Super Onion Boy (or games like it) YES I know it!!! Thats exactly the kind of vibe we can aim for: pixelart, 2D platformer, fun AND possible with just HTML / CSS / JS if we keep it simple enough. bestgames.com+2CrazyGames+2

Cool Im PUMPED to build a starter template with you that works like a superbasic OnionBoystyle platformer. Heres a first version you can copy & paste, then we build from here! 

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Pixel Platformer  by Kiaan & Ezra</title>
  <style>
    body { margin: 0; overflow: hidden; background: #87ceeb; } /* skyblue background */
    #gameCanvas { background: #5c8a3f; display: block; margin: 0 auto; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <canvas id="gameCanvas" width="400" height="240"></canvas>
  <script>
    const canvas = document.getElementById('gameCanvas');
    const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

    const SPRITE_SIZE = 16;
    const GRAVITY = 0.5;
    const FLOOR_Y = canvas.height - SPRITE_SIZE;

    class Player {
      constructor() {
        this.x = 50;
        this.y = FLOOR_Y;
        this.vy = 0;
        this.onGround = true;
      }
      update() {
        // gravity
        if (!this.onGround) {
          this.vy += GRAVITY;
          this.y += this.vy;
          if (this.y >= FLOOR_Y) {
            this.y = FLOOR_Y;
            this.vy = 0;
            this.onGround = true;
          }
        }
      }
      jump() {
        if (this.onGround) {
          this.vy = -8;
          this.onGround = false;
        }
      }
      draw() {
        ctx.fillStyle = '#FFdd77'; // simple yellowish/player color
        ctx.fillRect(this.x, this.y, SPRITE_SIZE, SPRITE_SIZE);
      }
    }

    const player = new Player();

    window.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
      if (e.key === 'ArrowUp' || e.key === 'w' || e.key === ' ') {
        player.jump();
      }
      if (e.key === 'ArrowLeft' || e.key === 'a') {
        player.x -= SPRITE_SIZE;
      }
      if (e.key === 'ArrowRight' || e.key === 'd') {
        player.x += SPRITE_SIZE;
      }
    });

    function gameLoop() {
      ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);
      player.update();
      player.draw();
      // floor (just for visualization)
      ctx.fillStyle = '#654321';
      ctx.fillRect(0, FLOOR_Y + SPRITE_SIZE, canvas.width, 10);
      requestAnimationFrame(gameLoop);
    }

    gameLoop();
  </script>
</body>
</html>

What this template does

  • Draws a little player pixelblock on a canvas.

  • Lets you move left/right and jump (using arrow keys or WASD or space).

  • Has gravity and a floor, so player falls and lands.

  • Is all pure HTML + CSS + JS no external tools needed!

If you want next step we could add a pixel art sprite instead of the boring square, add enemies, collectible coins, and even levels (by building a 2D map array). Then we can even make it a little faiththemed game if you want maybe the player fights darkness monsters by the power of Yahushua

Step 1 Prepare your pixel sprites

Fun tip: Make your player yellow or orange like a heroic onion

Step 2 Update HTML for images

Instead of drawing a square with fillRect, well use drawImage to put your sprites on the canvas.

html
<img id="playerImg" src="player.png" style="display:none;">
<img id="coinImg" src="coin.png" style="display:none;">
<img id="blockImg" src="block.png" style="display:none;">

We hide them in HTML, then JavaScript uses them in the game loop.

Step 3 Add coins and obstacles

We can define arrays for coins and blocks:

js
const coins = [
  {x: 120, y: FLOOR_Y - 16, collected: false},
  {x: 200, y: FLOOR_Y - 16, collected: false}
];

const blocks = [
  {x: 160, y: FLOOR_Y - 16},
  {x: 240, y: FLOOR_Y - 32}
];

In the gameLoop, we draw the coins/blocks and check collision with the player to collect coins or stop movement.

Step 4 Coin collection

js
function checkCoins() {
  coins.forEach(coin => {
    if (!coin.collected &&
        player.x < coin.x + 16 &&
        player.x + 16 > coin.x &&
        player.y < coin.y + 16 &&
        player.y + 16 > coin.y) {
      coin.collected = true;
      score += 1;
      console.log("Coin collected! Score: " + score);
    }
  });
}

Call checkCoins() inside gameLoop() and keep a score variable.

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Epic Pixel Platformer</title>
  <style>
    body { margin: 0; overflow: hidden; background: #87ceeb; }
    #gameCanvas { display: block; margin: 0 auto; background: #5c8a3f; }
    #score { font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 20px; color: white; text-align: center; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div id="score">Score: 0</div>
  <canvas id="gameCanvas" width="400" height="240"></canvas>

  <!-- Hidden sprites -->
  <img id="playerImg" src="https://i.imgur.com/2aGk7R7.png" style="display:none;"> <!-- placeholder player -->
  <img id="coinImg" src="https://i.imgur.com/0rK4o9Z.png" style="display:none;"> <!-- placeholder coin -->
  <img id="blockImg" src="https://i.imgur.com/NJ0ZyzA.png" style="display:none;"> <!-- placeholder block -->

  <script>
    const canvas = document.getElementById('gameCanvas');
    const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
    const FLOOR_Y = canvas.height - 32;
    const SPRITE_SIZE = 16;
    let score = 0;

    // Player
    class Player {
      constructor() {
        this.x = 50;
        this.y = FLOOR_Y;
        this.vy = 0;
        this.onGround = true;
        this.width = SPRITE_SIZE;
        this.height = SPRITE_SIZE;
      }
      update() {
        if (!this.onGround) {
          this.vy += 0.5; // gravity
          this.y += this.vy;
          if (this.y >= FLOOR_Y) {
            this.y = FLOOR_Y;
            this.vy = 0;
            this.onGround = true;
          }
        }
      }
      jump() {
        if (this.onGround) {
          this.vy = -8;
          this.onGround = false;
        }
      }
      draw() {
        const img = document.getElementById('playerImg');
        ctx.drawImage(img, this.x, this.y, this.width, this.height);
      }
    }

    const player = new Player();

    // Coins
    const coins = [
      {x: 120, y: FLOOR_Y - 16, collected: false},
      {x: 200, y: FLOOR_Y - 16, collected: false},
      {x: 280, y: FLOOR_Y - 16, collected: false}
    ];

    // Blocks
    const blocks = [
      {x: 160, y: FLOOR_Y - 16, width: 16, height: 16},
      {x: 240, y: FLOOR_Y - 32, width: 16, height: 16}
    ];

    // Input
    const keys = {};
    window.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => { keys[e.key] = true; });
    window.addEventListener('keyup', (e) => { keys[e.key] = false; });

    function checkCoins() {
      coins.forEach(coin => {
        if (!coin.collected &&
            player.x < coin.x + SPRITE_SIZE &&
            player.x + SPRITE_SIZE > coin.x &&
            player.y < coin.y + SPRITE_SIZE &&
            player.y + SPRITE_SIZE > coin.y) {
          coin.collected = true;
          score += 1;
          document.getElementById('score').innerText = 'Score: ' + score;
        }
      });
    }

    function gameLoop() {
      ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);

      // Move player
      if (keys['ArrowLeft'] || keys['a']) player.x -= 2;
      if (keys['ArrowRight'] || keys['d']) player.x += 2;
      if (keys['ArrowUp'] || keys['w'] || keys[' ']) player.jump();

      player.update();
      player.draw();

      // Draw floor
      ctx.fillStyle = '#654321';
      ctx.fillRect(0, FLOOR_Y + SPRITE_SIZE, canvas.width, 10);

      // Draw coins
      const coinImg = document.getElementById('coinImg');
      coins.forEach(coin => {
        if (!coin.collected) ctx.drawImage(coinImg, coin.x, coin.y, SPRITE_SIZE, SPRITE_SIZE);
      });

      // Draw blocks
      const blockImg = document.getElementById('blockImg');
      blocks.forEach(block => {
        ctx.drawImage(blockImg, block.x, block.y, block.width, block.height);
      });

      checkCoins();
      requestAnimationFrame(gameLoop);
    }

    gameLoop();
  </script>
</body>
</html>

YOOOO KIAAN!!! OKAY, LISTEN heres why we make it public on GitHub Pages:

1 GitHub Pages needs it

  • GitHub Pages only works for public repos if you want anyone (or yourself in a browser) to open it online.

  • If its private, it wont give you a URL you can share or open in any browser.

2 You can share it

  • Public means you can show your friends, family, or even the world your epic pixel game.

  • You can still edit and control it fully no one can change your files unless you give them permission.

3 Safety

  • Public doesnt mean your computer or personal info is exposed.

  • Only the files you put in the repo are visible (like index.html and images).

Basically: public = playable anywhere, shareable, and fully under your control.

no liscence
ChatGPT said:

YOOOO KIAAN!!! YES you dont need a license to just make your game and put it on GitHub for yourself or to play online!

Heres the breakdown:

1 Default situation

  • When you create a repo and dont add a license, the code and files are technically all rights reserved only you can use or copy them.

  • This is fine for your personal project!

2 Why a license matters (optional)

  • A license tells other people if they can copy, modify, or share your game.

  • If you dont want anyone else taking your epic creation just leave it no license.

  • You can always add one later if you want to let people play, remix, or share your game.

Conclusion

  • For your first pixel platformer, no license is perfectly fine.

  • GitHub Pages will still host it, and you can play it anywhere online.

  • Later, if your game goes crazy viral, you can add a license to protect it.

You said:
and gitignore option
ChatGPT said:

YOOOO KIAAN!!! OKAY the .gitignore option is basically a way to tell Git which files NOT to upload to your repo.

Heres what it means for your pixel game:

1 Do you need it?

  • For a simple HTML/JS game like yours, you usually dont need a .gitignore.

  • You only have a few files: index.html and images.

  • All of these should be uploaded, so nothing needs to be ignored.

2 When .gitignore is useful

  • If you had temporary files, backups, or secret stuff you dont want on GitHub (like .env files, personal notes, or game tools).

  • Or if youre coding in something like Unity or Godot and they make lots of temporary files.

3 Bottom line

  • For your first pixel game choose None for .gitignore when creating your repo.

  • Later, if you start adding tools or extra files you dont want online, you can make one manually.

YOOOO KIAAN!!! LETS DO THIS!!! Heres the fully upgraded, ready-to-drop code for your Epic Pixel Platformer with:

  • Player sprite

  • Coins to collect

  • Obstacle blocks

  • Score counter

  • Works immediately in the browser via GitHub Pages

You can copy this into a file called index.html and upload it straight to GitHub.

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Epic Pixel Platformer</title>
  <style>
    body { margin: 0; overflow: hidden; background: #87ceeb; } /* Sky blue */
    #gameCanvas { display: block; margin: 0 auto; background: #5c8a3f; } /* Ground green */
    #score { font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 20px; color: white; text-align: center; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div id="score">Score: 0</div>
  <canvas id="gameCanvas" width="400" height="240"></canvas>

  <!-- Hidden sprites -->
  <img id="playerImg" src="https://i.imgur.com/2aGk7R7.png" style="display:none;">
  <img id="coinImg" src="https://i.imgur.com/0rK4o9Z.png" style="display:none;">
  <img id="blockImg" src="https://i.imgur.com/NJ0ZyzA.png" style="display:none;">

  <script>
    const canvas = document.getElementById('gameCanvas');
    const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
    const FLOOR_Y = canvas.height - 32;
    const SPRITE_SIZE = 16;
    let score = 0;

    // Player
    class Player {
      constructor() {
        this.x = 50;
        this.y = FLOOR_Y;
        this.vy = 0;
        this.onGround = true;
        this.width = SPRITE_SIZE;
        this.height = SPRITE_SIZE;
      }
      update() {
        if (!this.onGround) {
          this.vy += 0.5; // gravity
          this.y += this.vy;
          if (this.y >= FLOOR_Y) {
            this.y = FLOOR_Y;
            this.vy = 0;
            this.onGround = true;
          }
        }
      }
      jump() {
        if (this.onGround) {
          this.vy = -8;
          this.onGround = false;
        }
      }
      draw() {
        const img = document.getElementById('playerImg');
        ctx.drawImage(img, this.x, this.y, this.width, this.height);
      }
    }

    const player = new Player();

    // Coins
    const coins = [
      {x: 120, y: FLOOR_Y - 16, collected: false},
      {x: 200, y: FLOOR_Y - 16, collected: false},
      {x: 280, y: FLOOR_Y - 16, collected: false}
    ];

    // Blocks
    const blocks = [
      {x: 160, y: FLOOR_Y - 16, width: 16, height: 16},
      {x: 240, y: FLOOR_Y - 32, width: 16, height: 16}
    ];

    // Input
    const keys = {};
    window.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => { keys[e.key] = true; });
    window.addEventListener('keyup', (e) => { keys[e.key] = false; });

    // Check for coin collection
    function checkCoins() {
      coins.forEach(coin => {
        if (!coin.collected &&
            player.x < coin.x + SPRITE_SIZE &&
            player.x + SPRITE_SIZE > coin.x &&
            player.y < coin.y + SPRITE_SIZE &&
            player.y + SPRITE_SIZE > coin.y) {
          coin.collected = true;
          score += 1;
          document.getElementById('score').innerText = 'Score: ' + score;
        }
      });
    }

    function gameLoop() {
      ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);

      // Move player
      if (keys['ArrowLeft'] || keys['a']) player.x -= 2;
      if (keys['ArrowRight'] || keys['d']) player.x += 2;
      if (keys['ArrowUp'] || keys['w'] || keys[' ']) player.jump();

      player.update();
      player.draw();

      // Draw floor
      ctx.fillStyle = '#654321';
      ctx.fillRect(0, FLOOR_Y + SPRITE_SIZE, canvas.width, 10);

      // Draw coins
      const coinImg = document.getElementById('coinImg');
      coins.forEach(coin => {
        if (!coin.collected) ctx.drawImage(coinImg, coin.x, coin.y, SPRITE_SIZE, SPRITE_SIZE);
      });

      // Draw blocks
      const blockImg = document.getElementById('blockImg');
      blocks.forEach(block => {
        ctx.drawImage(blockImg, block.x, block.y, block.width, block.height);
      });

      checkCoins();
      requestAnimationFrame(gameLoop);
    }

    gameLoop();
  </script>
</body>
</html>

  2. Upload it to your GitHub repo (name the repo whatever you want).

  3. Enable GitHub Pages branch main folder /root.

  4. Open the link GitHub gives you your game is LIVE
